			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Actually passwords should not be based on real words.  Cryptic passwords for example: Oex32y$f would be far better then anything containing a dictionary word.  Far harder to remember but much more secure to cracks.<BR>
<BR>
Secondly it was stated that these people were social engineered out of their account information, and while it is unwise to trust anyone with such important information they did it in the belief that he was their friend whom he was posing as.  No amount of password security will protect you if you give your account information out.  <BR>
<BR>
Debating the word hacker is truly dead, it is so far deviated from its original meaning no amount of pr will change it back.  Might as well just let it go its a battle thats already been lost long ago.<BR>
<BR>
Lastly this kid hopefully learned his lesson, and will not ever do something like this to people again.
				</font>
